DOCUMENT();
############################################################ # Load Macros ############################################################ loadMacros( "PGstandard.pl", "PGML.pl", "AnswerFormatHelp.pl", "PCCmacros.pl", "contextForm.pl", "parserLinearRelation.pl", "PGcourse.pl", ); COMMENT('Authored in PreTeXt');
############################################################ # Header ############################################################ TEXT(beginproblem());
############################################################ # PG Setup Code ############################################################ Context("LinearRelation"); Context()->variables->are(t => "Real"); Context()->operators->undefine("/"); Parser::Number::NoDecimals(); $equation = Formula("105-3t=40");
############################################################ # Body ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML In a science lab, a container had [`21`] ounces of water at 9:00[$NBSP]*AM. Water has been evaporating at the rate of [`3`] ounces every [`5`] minutes. When will there be [`8`] ounces of water left?
[@KeyboardInstructions('Write an equation for this scenario, using [`t`] as the variable. Then do what is needed to clear the denominators. Enter the equation with cleared denominators.')@]**
[_]{$equation}{16}
END_PGML
############################################################ # Solution ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION Since the container has been losing [`3`] oz of water every [`5`] minutes, it loses [`\frac{3}{5}`] oz every minute. At [`t`] minutes past 9:00[$NBSP]*AM, the container will have lost [`\frac{3}{5}t`] oz of water. Since the initial amount was [`21`] oz, the amount of water in the container (in oz) can be modeled by [`21-\frac{3}{5}t\text{.}`]
So to work out when there would be only [`8`] oz of water left, we write the following equation. Note there is a denominator of [`5\text{,}`] which we can clear.
[```\newcommand{\multiplyleft}[2][\cdot]{{\highlight{{#2#1{}}}}}\newcommand{\amp}{&} \begin{aligned} 21-\frac{3}{5}t\amp=8\\ \multiplyleft{5}\left(21-\frac{3}{5}t\right)\amp=\multiplyleft{5}8\\ 5\cdot21-5\cdot\frac{3}{5}t\amp=40\\ 105-3t\amp=40 \end{aligned} ```]
From here it is straightforward to use steps from Section[$NBSP]*1.2 to solve the equation. You can try that on your own and you should find that it will take between [`21`] and [`22`] minutes for the container to only have [`8`] ounces of water left.
END_PGML_SOLUTION
############################################################ # End Problem ############################################################
ENDDOCUMENT();
